I now have the full picture. The diagnosis is crystal clear. Here is everything you need.

---

## Diagnosis

The nav has `position: sticky` (not `fixed`). A sticky element is **still part of document flow** — it scrolls with its scroll container, not with the viewport. The critical architectural fact is:

> **A sticky element sticks relative to its nearest scrolling ancestor, not the viewport.**

The layout is:
```
<div.siteWrapper>          ← flex column, min-height: 100vh
  <nav.nav>                ← position: sticky, top: 0
  <div.contentArea>        ← overflow-x: auto   ← THIS IS THE SCROLL CONTAINER
    <div.contentAreaInner> ← min-width: 672px
  <SiteFooter>
```

When the viewport is narrower than 672px on a `pointer: fine` device, `.contentArea` becomes an `overflow-x: auto` scroll container. Because `.contentArea` is an **overflow container**, it also becomes a new scroll boundary for any sticky descendants. But the nav is the sticky element's **ancestor**, sitting *outside* `.contentArea`. The real trap is that `.siteWrapper` has no explicit `overflow` set — so the browser's document-level scroll container extends upward to `<html>`/`<body>`.

The actual bug: `.contentAreaInner` at `min-width: 672px` inside `.contentArea` at `overflow-x: auto` causes the **content area** to scroll independently, but at extremely narrow viewports (< 320px real device width), the `672px` floor still implicitly expands the *document* width — the `.siteWrapper` has no width constraint of its own, so the nav, which is full-width relative to `.siteWrapper`, expands to fill whatever width `.siteWrapper` is forced to by its widest child. Since `.contentAreaInner`'s `min-width: 672px` bleeds through `.contentArea`'s box if `overflow-x: auto` isn't producing a true scrollport boundary at the document level, on very narrow real viewports the document itself overflows and the browser disables its own horizontal scroll.

The precise failure chain:
1. `<html>` and `<body>` have no explicit `overflow` or `width` constraint
2. `.siteWrapper` is a flex column with no `max-width` or `width: 100%` set defensively
3. `.contentAreaInner` at `min-width: 672px` makes `.contentArea`'s scroll content 672px wide
4. `.contentArea` has `overflow-x: auto`, which should contain this — but `overflow-x: auto` only creates a scrollport if the element itself has a defined width ceiling. Without `width: 100%` or `max-width: 100vw` on `.contentArea`, at sub-320px viewports it can stretch to accommodate the child
5. The nav, being a sibling of `.contentArea` inside `.siteWrapper`, inherits the expanded width and gets clipped on the right with no horizontal scroll possible at the document level

---

## Root Cause

**AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome.**

The existing AP-067 covers the first-order mistake (putting `min-width` on the root wrapper itself). This is a **second-order variant**: the `overflow-x: auto` containment on `.contentArea` is correct in principle, but it requires `.contentArea` to have a width ceiling (`width: 100%` or `max-width: 100vw`) so it actually forms a scrollport boundary rather than stretching to fit its content. Without the ceiling, at sub-320px real viewports the document itself expands and the nav — a sibling outside the scroll container — inherits that expansion and clips.

The invariant that was missing: **any element that uses `overflow-x: auto` as a scroll container boundary must also carry `width: 100%` (or equivalent) so it cannot stretch wider than its own containing block.** Without both declarations together, `overflow-x: auto` is not a real containment — it's a conditional one that fails when the parent has no width floor.

---

## Fix

Three files need changes, each for a distinct reason:

### 1. `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`

Add `width: 100%` to `.contentArea` in the media query block so it forms a true scrollport boundary. Also add defensive `width: 100%` to `.siteWrapper` so it can never be stretched wider than the viewport by any descendant.

```scss
@use '../../../styles' as *;

// ── ZERO RADIUS OVERRIDE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Portfolio branding: all border-radius is 0 on the public site.
// This overrides CSS custom properties so DS components (Badge, Card, Input,
// Dialog, Tooltip, etc.) all render with sharp corners when inside the (site)
// route group. Structural exceptions (Avatar, Toggle, Slider, ProgressBar)
// restore their radius locally in their own SCSS modules.
// See docs/design/branding.md §1 for the full rule.

.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  // ⚠ CRITICAL: This width constraint is load-bearing. Do NOT remove it.
  // Without `width: 100%`, a wide descendant (e.g. `.contentAreaInner`'s
  // min-width floor) can stretch `.siteWrapper` beyond the viewport, causing
  // the nav — which is full-width relative to this wrapper — to clip on the
  // right with no document-level horizontal scroll. The nav must always be
  // reachable at every viewport width. See AP-067 (second-order variant) and
  // FB-NNN in docs/design-feedback-log.md.
  width: 100%;

  --portfolio-radius-xs: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-sm: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-md: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-lg: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-xl: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-2xl: 0;
  // --portfolio-radius-full is intentionally NOT overridden.
  // Structural exceptions (Avatar, Toggle, Slider, ProgressBar) depend on it
  // for circular shapes. Badge pill shape should not be used on the portfolio —
  // always pass shape="squared" per docs/design/branding.md §1.2.
}

.contentArea {
  flex: 1;
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1;
  // Allow the flex child to shrink below its intrinsic min content width so
  // the overflow scroll container below can take effect at narrow viewports.
  min-width: 0;
}

.contentAreaInner {
  // Default: no width constraint — content fills contentArea naturally.
}

// ── DESKTOP MIN-WIDTH FLOOR (CONTENT ONLY) ────────────────────────────────
// Below the sm breakpoint on mouse-driven devices, the page *content* gets a
// 672px floor with horizontal scroll so case studies and other composed
// surfaces render at their intended width. Nav and SiteFooter are siblings
// of `.contentArea`, so they stay fluid to the actual viewport and fall back
// to their mobile layouts — functional chrome must always be reachable and
// readable at any width. Scoped to `pointer: fine` so touch devices (which
// have their own phone composition at any width) are unaffected. See FB-147,
// FB-149 and `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10.
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea {
    // Contain the horizontal overflow inside `.contentArea` so it does NOT
    // grow the document width — siblings (Nav, SiteFooter) stay at viewport
    // width and remain fully responsive.
    overflow-x: auto;
    // ⚠ CRITICAL: `width: 100%` is required here alongside `overflow-x: auto`.
    // Without it, `.contentArea` can stretch to match its 672px child at
    // sub-320px viewport widths, expanding the document and clipping the nav.
    // `overflow-x: auto` only forms a true scrollport when the element has a
    // width ceiling. `width: 100%` provides that ceiling. See AP-067.
    width: 100%;
  }

  .contentAreaInner {
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm;
  }
}
```

### 2. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — Amend AP-067

Append the second-order variant clause to the existing AP-067 entry:

```markdown
<a id="ap-067"></a>
## AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome

**Status: ACTIVE**

**Trigger:** Setting `min-width` on a wrapper element (`.siteWrapper`, `<body>`, the layout root) when that wrapper is also the containing block for functional chrome — nav bars, footers, skip links, admin toolbars. Equivalently: using `overflow-x: auto` as a scroll-container boundary on an element that lacks an explicit `width: 100%` ceiling, which produces the same nav-clipping failure via a different path.

**Why it's wrong:**

*Primary form:* A `min-width` on the wrapper expands the entire document, including the nav. At sub-minimum viewport widths the browser disables horizontal scrolling (document scroll is asymmetric — vertical scrolls are always available, but horizontal scroll only activates if the document overflows). The nav is then clipped on the right side and unreachable — a functional accessibility failure.

*Second-order variant (sub-320px sticky-nav clip):* The `min-width` floor is correctly scoped to `.contentAreaInner` inside an `overflow-x: auto` scroll container (`.contentArea`). But if `.contentArea` lacks `width: 100%`, at extremely narrow viewports the element stretches to match its 672px child rather than forming a true scrollport boundary. The document grows, the nav — a sibling of `.contentArea`, full-width relative to `.siteWrapper` — inherits the expanded width, and the right-side clip returns. The fix requires **both** `overflow-x: auto` AND `width: 100%` on the scroll container, and **`width: 100%` on `.siteWrapper`** so no descendant can ever inflate the document root.

**Invariant:** `overflow-x: auto` is only a real scrollport boundary when the element also has a width ceiling (`width: 100%` or `max-width: 100vw`). The two declarations are always required together.

**Correct alternative:**

```scss
// Root wrapper — must never stretch beyond viewport
.siteWrapper {
  width: 100%; // ← load-bearing; do not remove
}

// Scroll container for the min-width floor
.contentArea {
  overflow-x: auto;
  width: 100%; // ← required partner to overflow-x: auto
  min-width: 0;
}

// Min-width floor lives HERE only — never on siteWrapper
.contentAreaInner {
  min-width: $elan-bp-sm; // 672px
}
```

**Rule for agents:** Never set `min-width` on any element that is an ancestor of functional chrome (nav, footer, admin bar, skip links). The min-width floor belongs exclusively on the *content* element, one level inside a properly bounded scroll container.

**Frustration caused:** 3 rounds (FB-147, FB-149, FB-NNN). FB-147 introduced the floor. FB-149 corrected its scope to content-only. FB-NNN revealed the second-order variant: the scroll container must carry `width: 100%` or the containment silently fails at sub-320px widths.

**References:** FB-147, FB-149, FB-NNN, `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10
```

### 3. `docs/design-feedback-log.md` — Append FB-225

Add at the top of the log (newest first), incrementing from the current last entry (FB-224):

```markdown
#### FB-225: "On viewports narrower than 320px, the entire page including the fixed nav stops scrolling horizontally"

**UX Intent:** Functional chrome (nav, footer) must be reachable at every viewport width — including sub-320px widths that occur when a desktop browser window is dragged extremely narrow. A clipped, unreachable nav is an accessibility and usability failure regardless of how exotic the viewport is.

**Root Cause:** `.contentArea` carried `overflow-x: auto` to contain the 672px `min-width` floor inside it, but lacked `width: 100%`. At sub-320px viewports, without a width ceiling, `.contentArea` stretched to match its 672px child instead of forming a scrollport. This expanded `.siteWrapper` — which also lacked `width: 100%` — beyond the viewport, causing the browser to suppress document-level horizontal scroll and clipping the nav on the right. AP-067 (second-order variant): `overflow-x: auto` alone is not a scrollport boundary; it requires `width: 100%` as a mandatory partner.

**Resolution:**
- Added `width: 100%` to `.siteWrapper` (unconditional) in `layout.module.scss`
- Added `width: 100%` to `.contentArea` inside the `@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px})` block — paired with the existing `overflow-x: auto`
- Amended AP-067 in `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` to document the second-order variant and codify the invariant: `overflow-x: auto` and `width: 100%` are always required together on a scroll container

**Pattern extracted → `design.md` §6.10 + AP-067 (amended)**
```

---

## Principle

**AP-067 (amended) — the invariant in one sentence:**

> `overflow-x: auto` is only a real scrollport boundary when the element also carries `width: 100%`. The two declarations are always required together on any scroll container that uses a min-width floor. The min-width floor itself must never appear on any element that is an ancestor of functional chrome.

The deeper principle is that CSS overflow containment is **conditional**, not absolute. `overflow-x: auto` says "scroll if I overflow my *own* box" — but if the box itself has no width ceiling, it simply grows to avoid overflowing, and the scrollport never materialises. A browser's document-level horizontal scroll is also conditional in the same way: it only activates when content genuinely overflows `<html>`. If `.siteWrapper` has no `width: 100%` and a deep descendant is 672px wide, the document root considers that valid content width and refuses to offer horizontal scroll, since from its perspective nothing is overflowing. The result is the exact failure the user saw: a nav item visible on hover but unreachable.
